===Etymology===
Coined as {{m|en|Doomsday Machine}} by military strategist {{w|Herman Kahn}}.<ref>{{cite-book|author=Herman Kahn|authorlink=Herman Kahn|title=On Thermonuclear War|year=1960|publisher=Princeton University Press|pages=144–145|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/onthermonuclearw0000kahn/page/144/mode/2up|passage=I would like to start this section on “not looking or being too dangerous” with some comments on the strategic theory of three conceptualized devices, which I will call the Doomsday Machine, the Doomsday-in-a-Hurry Machine, and the Homicide Pact Machine.}}</ref>

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A hypothetical [[weapon]] (often a [[bomb]]) [[programmed]] to [[automatically]] be used in response to certain [[attack]]s, usually with very [[dire]] [[consequence]]s (such as the [[annihilation]] of the [[world]]).
#* {{quote-av|en|year=1964|author=Stanley Kubrick; Terry Southern; Peter George|title=Dr. Strangelove or: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb|role=Narrator|passage=For more than a year, ominous rumors had been privately circulating among high-level Western leaders that the Soviet Union had been at work on what was darkly hinted to be the ultimate weapon: a '''doomsday device'''.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Ben Stein|title=Wall Street, Run Amok|work=The New York Times|date=2008-04-27|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/27/business/27every.html|issn=0362-4331|passage=Of course, Henry M. Paulson Jr., the Treasury secretary, is calling for merging the S.E.C. with the easygoing Commodity Futures Trading Commission, in the financial equivalent of setting off a '''Doomsday Device'''.}}
# An [[extremely]] [[powerful]] [[weapon]].

